# GitHub Issue Workflow Rules

## **MANDATORY — PRECEDENCE**

- **Always use `--body-file` for issue comments.** Do not pass comment body inline to `gh issue comment` (e.g. `gh issue comment 3 --body "text"`). Inline bodies cause shell interpretation of backticks, `$`, and other characters. This rule has no exceptions when posting issue comments.
- **When in doubt, use the temp file.** For any issue comment that includes formatting, code, or special characters, write the message to a temp file and use `gh issue comment <number> --body-file <file>`.

## **Reusable body file (avoid delete prompts)**

- Use **one stable path per Cursor host process** under `/tmp`, so the agent **overwrites** the same file for each `gh issue comment` instead of creating and deleting unique paths (which can trigger repeated “remove file?” prompts).
- **Path:** `/tmp/cursor-gh-issue-comment-${CURSOR_PID}.md`
  - Prefer **`CURSOR_PID`** when the Cursor host sets it for the agent terminal.
  - If **`CURSOR_PID` is unset**, fall back to **`$$`** (current shell PID): `COMMENT_FILE="/tmp/cursor-gh-issue-comment-${CURSOR_PID:-$$}.md"`
- **Do not delete** that file after posting unless it contains secrets you must clear; the next comment overwrites it.

## **Core Principle**

When updating GitHub issues with comments that contain backticks, code blocks, or special characters, always use a temporary file to avoid shell interpretation issues.

## **TDD — red phase log on the issue (MANDATORY when issue-driven)**

When work maps to a GitHub issue, **strict TDD** requires posting **deliberately red** test output to that issue. See `.cursor/rules/strict-tdd-definition.mdc` → **Required Evidence** → **GitHub issue — red log**.

**Posting rules:**

1. Build the comment in the **reusable body file** under `/tmp` (see **Reusable body file** above; failure excerpts almost always contain `` ` ``, `$`, or paths—unsafe for inline `gh` `--body`).
2. Run `gh issue comment <N> --body-file <path>`. **Do not** delete that file by default (reuse next time).
3. The comment body **must** include a **timestamp** (UTC ISO 8601 in the text), **how tests were run**, and **failing test id(s) + a short verbatim excerpt** of the failure (minimal lines: which test, which assertion/message). **Do not** attach or paste a **complete** test run or full build transcript—**relevant excerpt only**; point to a local/CI log path if the full run matters.

This gives a durable, timestamped audit that tests **ran and failed for the right reason**, not only that they eventually passed.

## **When to close issues (branch vs `main`)**

- **Close when the work is done** on the branch where it was implemented (e.g. feature or release-prep branch). Do **not** wait for merge to `main` to close.
- **Merge to `main`** is part of the **final release process**, not a prerequisite for closing the issue in normal workflow.
- When commenting or closing, **name the branch** commits live on (e.g. “Implemented on `b7.6.0`, pushed”) so it is obvious where to find the work before release.

## **MANDATORY Workflow**

### **For Issue Comments:**

1. **Write message to reusable body file** — Path: `/tmp/cursor-gh-issue-comment-${CURSOR_PID:-$$}.md` (see **Reusable body file** above).

2. **Use `--body-file` flag** - Use `gh issue comment <number> --body-file <file>` to add the comment

3. **Close issue if needed** - Use `gh issue close <number> --reason completed` to close

4. **Reuse** — Keep the same `/tmp/cursor-gh-issue-comment-*.md` path; do not delete after each use unless you must clear sensitive content.

### **Example:**

```bash
COMMENT_FILE="/tmp/cursor-gh-issue-comment-${CURSOR_PID:-$$}.md"

# Write comment body (overwrites previous use of this path)
cat > "$COMMENT_FILE" << 'EOF'
✅ Issue completed!

**Implementation Details:**

- Added `ColorUtilities` for generating colors
- Updated `TaskItem.cardColor` to show user colors
EOF

# Add comment and close issue
gh issue comment 3 --body-file "$COMMENT_FILE"
gh issue close 3 --reason completed
```

## **Why This Matters**

- Prevents shell interpretation of backticks as command substitution
- Allows proper formatting with code blocks and special characters
- Ensures comments are posted correctly without parsing errors
- Maintains clean terminal output

## **When to Use**

- **Always** when issue comments contain:
  - Backticks (`` `code` ``)
  - Code blocks (```swift```)
  - Special shell characters ($, `, \, etc.)
  - Multi-line formatted text
  - Markdown formatting

## **Benefits**

- **Reliable** - No shell interpretation issues
- **Clean** - Proper formatting preserved
- **Consistent** - Same workflow every time
- **Safe** - No accidental command execution
